[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 58.3% of the global newly reported cases and 63.2% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 7 million cases. The USA reported 47.2% (71 484) of the newly confirmed cases in the region, and Brazil reported 29.9% (45 403), Colombia 5.3% (8037), Mexico 4.2% (6406), Peru 2.5% (3862), Argentina 2.4% (3623), and Chile 1.8% (2841).

- The European region reported 12.8% of the global newly reported cases and 16.3% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Kyrgyzstan reported 35.6% (11 883) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Russia reporting 18.6% (6234), Israel 5.8% (1946), Kazakhstan 5.4% (1808), Spain 4.2% (1400), Turkey 2.7% (926), Ukraine 2.5% (847), Romania 2.4% (799), the UK 2.0% (687), France 1.8 % (627), Uzbekistan 1.6% (547), Germany 1.5% (529), Azerbaijan 1.4% (471), and Armenia 1.3% (461).

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5.3% of the global newly reported cases and 6.2% of global newly reported fatalities. Saudi Arabia reported 18.9% (2613) of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran 17.2% (2379), Iraq 14.6% (2023), Pakistan 13.8% (1918), Oman 11.7% (1619), Egypt 5.1% (703), Kuwait 4.0% (553), Qatar 3.0% (421), and Bahrain 2.8% (389).

- The African region reported 7.1% of the global newly reported cases and 2.9% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 72.9% (13 373) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria 3.3% (600), Algeria 3.2% (593), Ghana 2.4% (447), Kenya 2.1% (389) and Madagascar 2.0% (378).

- The Western Pacific region reported 1.3% of the global newly reported cases and 0.29% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 52.6% (1735) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 20.0% (659), Australia 12.9% (425), Singapore 9.9% (327), China 2.4% (82), and South Korea 1.2% (39).

- The South East Asia region reported 15.2% of the global newly reported cases and 10.9% of global deaths. India reported 88.3% (34 884) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 7.6% (3034) and Indonesia 3.7% (1462).

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis, followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific representing the lowest daily caseload of all of the regions. The progression has been the initial "surge" in the Western Pacific region, followed by the surge in the European region and its decline, the entry and surging of the Americas region without any decrease, and the gradual and persistent increase in the South East Asia region, the increase then plateauing of the Eastern Mediterranean region, and the slow but steady increase in the Africa region and a slight increase in the Western Pacific region today [18 Jul 2020].

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 18 Jul 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. - Mod.UBA]

